1. Nf3 {Let's analyze in this chapter how we can play the Reversed-London setup if White gets too comfortable and goes for the KIA without any early and spicy c2-c4.} d5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2 Bf5 4. O-O e6 5. d3 h6 $1 {This is a significant move in order to punish the White setup. This way we prevent c4-cxd5 setups and we have a great practical answer that gave me a winning position against a strong GM.} 6. Nfd2 $5 {[%cal Ge2e4] This plan is pretty common against the London. White wants to push for e4 without wasting tempos with the queen or the rook. It is the most challenging for Black, as you can get steamrolled by the e,f, and g pawns in the blink of an eye.} Bh7 7. e4 Nf6 8. Nc3 Be7 9. f4 {White follows up with the usual expansion. Now we don't want to castle too fast and justify g4-g5.} a5 {Doing some business on the queenside before castling looks smart. As we'll see plenty in this chapter, a5-a4 fits very well with the London-esque lines.} (9... O-O 10. g4 $5 $14 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gf4f5] The permanent threat of e4-e5 and/or f4-f5 is very unpleasant in practice.}) 10. Qe2 a4 {[%cal Ga4a3]} 11. a3 {Allowing a4-a3 would be great to cronically pressure the c3 knight and to have the b4 square for our b8 knight as well.} dxe4 {Now that Nbd7 is imminent, we want to have room for the f6 knight on d5 in case of e4-e5.} 12. dxe4 Qc7 13. g4 Nbd7 14. Kh1 b5 $132 {Now, g7-g5 could be an interesting idea to get the dark squares, as Nc4 is not possible anymore. This position requires some practice, but it doesn't look easy at all to follow up the attack for White.} *

