1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2 Bf5 4. O-O e6 5. d3 h6 $1 6. c4 {I'll put this 6. c4 in this chapter as it is the more passive one and we are thrilled to face it.} dxc4 7. dxc4 {[%csl Rc4,Gc6] White is already much worse statically and needs to be careful. Playing 5. ... h6 is key as White cannot bring down the light-squared bishop and the c6 pawn completely paralyzes White's position. This pawn structure can be seen in 1. d4 d6 2. c4 e5 3. dxe5? dxe5 and Black is already on the driver's seat. White cannot push the queenside reliably and the c4 pawn gives very nice black squares on c5 and b4. We aim to exchange as few pieces as possible so our opponent messes up the lack of threats and utility with the space.} (7. d4 $1 {This weird pawn sacrifice was played a couple of times by young promising Indians with inferior results. It is much much better than dxc4. White technically gets a small Catalan-ish advantage as h7-h6 is not very useful here. But it feels like a Slav with g3 so we are excellent anyway. At least White is fighting properly here.} Nf6 8. Nbd2 Be7 9. Nxc4 O-O 10. Nfe5 $1 {[%cal Rd1b3,Rf1d1] To prevent b7-b5 counterattaks and now Qb3-Rd1 might be an idea.} (10. b3 Nbd7 11. Bb2 b5 $1 12. Ncd2 Rc8 $36 {0-1 (55) Aditya,M (2438) -Lazavik,D (2436) Tornelo INT 2020}) 10... Be4 $5 $132 {This might be the best outcome for White but it doesn't look to me that black is in any danger soon.}) 7... Nd7 $1 {I feel it is more practical to keep the queens on the board as we have an excellent square on c7 or c8 and the White queen doesn't really know where to go.} 8. Nc3 Ngf6 $11 9. Bf4 Be7 10. Qe1 (10. Bd6 a5 $5 {[%cal Gd7c5] Feels simpler. 10. ... Bxd6 and Qe7 is also excellent. Now Nc5 is coming and we seize the dark squares and also prevent e2-e4.} 11. Na4 O-O $15 {[%cal Gf6e4]}) (10. Re1 Bh7 11. e4 Nc5 $15 12. Nd4 a5 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Gf6d7]} 13. e5 $6 Nfd7 $17 {[%cal Yh7b1] A great example on how White cannot even expand or gain space reliably. Now, g7-g5 is a serious threat, and the h7 bishop slices through the position swiftly. Black won very quickly in 0-1 (28) Plenkovic,Z (2386)-Jovanic,O (2467) Zadar 2014} 14. Nd5 cxd5 15. cxd5 O-O 16. Qg4 Kh8 17. Rad1 exd5 18. Nf5 Bxf5 19. Qxf5 Nb6 20. Bxh6 gxh6 21. Qh5 Bg5 22. h4 Ne6 23. Bxd5 Nxd5 24. Qf3 Nec7 25. hxg5 Qxg5 26. Re4 f5 27. Rh4 f4 28. Qh1 Ra6 {0-1 (28) Plenkovic,Z (2386)-Jovanic,O (2467) Zadar 2014}) 10... g5 $5 {This move was even suggested a move before by the engine, so I felt it made a lot of sense here! We prevent White from exchanging any piece and restrict our opponent even more.} 11. Bc1 e5 12. b3 Qc7 13. Bb2 O-O 14. e4 (14. h4 g4 15. Nd2 Bg6 $1 $132 {[%csl Rb2,Rc3,Rd2][%cal Gf6h5,Gf7f5] Was my idea during the game as Nde4 is answered with Nh5! and we keep making fun of the lack of proper space for White to maneuver.}) 14... Bg6 $15 {[%csl Gb4,Gc5,Gd4][%cal Gf8e8,Ga8d8] Got an excellent position that later on was a winning position but ended up spoiling it. I hope you can finish my work :). We have total control of the position, and White is too weak on the dark squares and has too many pieces. ½-½ (51) Bogosavljevic,B (2533)-Alonso Rosell,A (2563) Germany 2023} *

