1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2 Bf5 4. O-O e6 5. d3 h6 $1 6. Nbd2 {[%cal Ge2e4] The most common approach. White can now follow up with e2-e4 or with b2-b3.} Nf6 7. b3 $5 {This is the most common plan to have both fianchettos.} (7. Qe1 {Remember 7. Re1 is a bit useless as e2-e4 is not even a threat due to the pin on the d file.} Be7 8. e4 Bh7 9. Ne5 O-O 10. f4 a5 $1 {[%cal Ga5a4] We play the same plan as usual.} 11. Kh1 (11. a4 Na6 $15 {[%cal Ga6b4] This is too easy for black.}) 11... a4 12. g4 {Looks menacing but not too dangerous.} dxe4 {It is technically unnecessary, but it makes sense to open the a bit position to dilute the White attack.} 13. dxe4 Nbd7 $15 {[%cal Gf6d7,Gd7c5] The expansion through the queenside gives us a very healthy counterplay.}) (7. c4 $5 {[%cal Gc4d5] Since now dxc4 is impossible, we need to look for cxd5 ideas.} Nbd7 {It is important now to prevent cxd5-Qb3 or e2-e4 ideas depending on which pawn retakes d5.} 8. cxd5 (8. b3 {Now White can transpose to the usual plan. I'll give another approach to face this structure that gave me a couple of wins OTB. Maybe you like it even more than the main one!} Bc5 {Since White doesn't really want to play d3-d4, we can stay here and give room to the queen on e7 if needed.} 9. Bb2 O-O 10. a3 a5 11. Ra2 (11. Bc3 Qe7 {[%csl Ga3]} 12. Qc1 Rfe8 $1 13. Qb2 e5 $15 {This is a good example of how this line can be a bit more ambitious and useful.}) (11. Qc2 Qe7 $15 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gb7b5] We want to push for e6-e5 or even b7-b5, depending on how White plays. White doesn't really have any active plan as b3-b4 is impossible.}) 11... Qb6 $15 {[%cal Gf8e8,Yc5f8,Gb6a7,Ya5b4] Here we can copy the idea we gave in the main line, as Qa7 prevents any b3-b4 ideas.}) 8... cxd5 $1 9. e4 Bh7 $11 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gf8c5,Yd5e4] We don't want to open up the position for the g2 bishop. You just need to know that e4-e5 is wrong, as Ng8-Ne7 is a great rerouting. So don't go playing Be7 carelessly.}) 7... Be7 8. Bb2 O-O 9. Re1 {[%cal Ge2e4]} (9. c4 a5 10. a3 {[%cal Gb3b4] Here White has some ideas. Bc3-Qb2-b4 and Ra2-Qa1. We have interesting approaches against both.} Bh7 11. Ra2 (11. Qc2 Qb6 {Looks good enough to slow down White's plan.} 12. Bc3 (12. Rfb1 {This move always has issues with f2.} Ng4 $1 {[%cal Gb6f2,Gg4f2]} 13. Bd4 c5 14. Bb2 Nc6 $15 {[%csl Ra1,Rb1] The White position is a bit silly.}) 12... c5 $5 13. cxd5 exd5 {[%cal Gb8c6]}) (11. Bc3 {[%cal Gb3b4]} c5 $5 {This change of pace can be tricky but we focus on not allowing our opponent to play a pleasant and simple plan with b4-b5 while our h7 bishop is out of the game.} 12. cxd5 (12. Ne5 d4 $1 13. Bb2 Nbd7 $15 {White lacks space.}) 12... exd5 {[%cal Gd5d4]} 13. e4 $5 {You need to expect e2-e4 in almost every position in this setup.} (13. d4 Nc6 $15 {This is an excellent isolated pawn game and our h7 bishop is very happy.}) 13... dxe4 14. dxe4 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 $11 {Our pawn structure is not ideal but I don't think White has anything else than some compensation.}) 11... Qb6 $5 12. Qa1 Rd8 {[%csl Ra1,Ga7,Gc5][%cal Ge7c5,Gb6a7,Ya5b4] With this move we allow Ne8 or Bf8 ideas later on. Now Just Nbd7 would be a great follow-up.} 13. Bc3 Qa7 $1 $15 {[%cal Ya7a2] This hidden idea makes it very hard for White to do anything productive. We could go for c5-Nc6 and get some space in the center if we feel ambitious. Another option could be Nbd7 and maybe b7-b5 plans after Rfc8 or even a passive approach with Bf8 could be interesting.}) (9. Qe1 {[%cal Ge2e4]} a5 {As usual we want White to react and then we play accordingly.} 10. e4 Bh7 11. a4 (11. a3 Nfd7 $5 {Many moves are fine but again I feel being safe and playing ahead of our opponent is the best practical approach.} 12. Qe2 c5 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gf8e8] Now we shifted the approach and White doesn't have any of the typical plans available and our play is pretty easy with Nc6-Re8-Bf8 and let White overextend. We always have the shadow of a5-a4 in our favour.}) 11... Na6 {[%cal Ga6b4,Yf3e5,Yf6d7] We have this sweet b4 square and we want to counter Ne5 with Nd7 as usual.} 12. Qe2 Nd7 $1 {[%csl Rd2,Re2,Rf3,Rg2][%cal Gf8e8,Gb7b5] We got ahead of all White ideas and now we simply have in mind to play useful moves like Re8 and go for b5 eventually. White doesn't have any active play or breakthrough.}) (9. Ne5 {[%cal Ge2e4]} Nbd7 {We challenge the knight inmediately. We don't want White to press easily with f4-g4.} 10. e4 Bh7 11. Nxd7 Nxd7 12. Qe2 a5 $1 {As usual we want to force White to define the queenside pawn structure.} 13. a4 Bf6 $1 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Gb7b5] We want to seize the dark squares on the queenside and we always have b7-b5 themes later on.} 14. e5 Be7 15. f4 b5 {[%cal Gb5a4,Yd7c5,Yc5a6] Taking on a4 and looking to actively press with the knight with Nc5-Na6-Nb4 looks very easy and White's attack is very far from real as the queenside is too exposed. In the case of 13. a3, now we could follow with 15. ... a4! 16. b4 c5! and we manage to open the queenside as well.}) 9... a5 $5 {We want to wait for the b8 knight to develop depending how White plays.} 10. e4 Bh7 11. a4 (11. a3 $5 {White wants to remain a bit more flexible.} Nbd7 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Gf3e5]} 12. e5 (12. Qe2 b5 $132 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gf8d8] After Qb6 I don't really see what White is doing after completing the development. We can also go for 12. ... Rc8 and wait a bit for our opponent to let them make a mistake. Be careful not to play Re8 as e5! would leave us without a proper square for the f6 knight.}) 12... Ne8 $15 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gc6c5,Ge8c7,Gb7b5] Now it is quite obvious to follow up with Nc7-c5-b5 and expand all the way as if it was a typical KIA.}) 11... Na6 {[%cal Gf6d7,Gd7c5,Ga6b4,Yb7b5] This move makes a lot of sense as we head towards b4. I'd say it is incredibly bad for White the tendency of the position.} 12. e5 (12. Ne5 Bb4 $1 $15 {[%csl Re4] And we force White to play c2-c3 or exd5, shutting down White's plan.}) 12... Nd7 13. Nd4 Nb4 $15 {[%csl Rh7] In general Nc5 and b5 is an excellent plan that kills the entire queenside eventually. We have an amazing bishop on h7 as an attacker and defender.} 14. h4 (14. Bf1 Nb8 $5 {[%cal Gc6c5,Gb8c6,Yb7b5] We aim for c5-Nc6 or even Qd7-b5 if White gets too comfortable. 14. ... Qc7 was a bit off after 15. N2f3 c2-c3 is a threat so b5 doesn't work well here.}) 14... Qc7 $1 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Gb7b5] Followed by b5 and we get an impressive counterplay.} *

