1. Nf3 {This chapter is the key. Usually this setup wasn't praised in high elo as all the early c4 put Black into serious trouble after the typical cxd5-Qb3-d3-Qc2-e4 plans. We'll try to take the pawn, claim everything is alright, and force White to remember a quite old-fashioned line with new ideas.} d5 2. g3 {From my experience playing this line with White, Black needs precision in every line. Maybe the most reliable and solid is 2. ... g6, but the dull symmetrical Grunfelds are also tricky.} (2. c4 c6 3. b3 {Usually, people that want to play with g2-g3 go for this. Hence why Bg4!? could be an extra interesting option.} (3. Qc2 {This obscure move, taken from my course on the Benoni to prevent London players from having any fun, with the idea to prevent Bf5 would likely transpose to some known territory in the main slav after:} Nf6 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Yc8f5]}) 3... Bf5 {This setup is perfectly fine for black. I have 2 games with Bg4 that are also an example of how good this is.} (3... Bg4 4. Ne5 (4. g3 e6 {Here I'd recommend going for the safe approach with Bd6 and black is more than fine. Bxf3 nowadays is not great and the position is too solid for both to create an opening.}) 4... Bf5 5. g4 Be6 6. e3 Nd7 7. Bb2 Ngf6 8. Be2 h5 $1 9. gxh5 Bf5 10. cxd5 Nxe5 11. Bxe5 Qxd5 {0-1 (11) Cuenca Jimenez,F (2177)-Alonso Rosell,A (2529) San Agustin 2012}) 4. Ba3 $5 {The only added idea that can surprise us.} (4. Bb2 e6 5. e3 {This setup is very harmless, considering we have the bishop out of the pawnchain.} h6 6. d4 (6. Be2 Nf6 7. Rg1 {This is a bit absurd. We have too much counterplay.} Nbd7 8. h3 Bh7 9. g4 Nc5 $17 {[%csl Rf8,Gh7][%cal Gc5d3] White is already close to resign. We can always castle long.}) 6... Nf6 7. Nc3 Nbd7 8. Bd3 Bb4 {[%cal Gb4a5] This setup is arduous for White to crack and we even have some initiative. Now we just want to play Ba5 in general (that way we prevent future e3-e4, and just castle and put both rooks into play.}) 4... Nd7 5. e3 {If White goes for g3-Bg2 we can even play with e5!?.} e6 6. Bxf8 Nxf8 {At least this should be more than fine.}) 2... c6 3. Bg2 Bf5 4. O-O (4. c4 {Maybe the most dangerous version.} dxc4 {Since we want to avoid those cxd5-d3 variations that are very tricky, we get into the mud and challenge our opponent. Usually White plays this setup to have a long game, not to be very well prepared, so we will force them to do the hard work.} 5. Na3 {The mainline by far.} (5. O-O e6 $1 {Transposes}) 5... e5 $1 {A very well known trick. From now on - White is more or less forced to know everything in advance and play with precision.} 6. Nxc4 e4 7. Nfe5 {The critical line. White needs to know a lot in here, and we have many ways to play.} (7. Nh4 {Has been played many times but we are doing great already.} Be6 {[%cal Gg7g5]} 8. Ne3 {A must.} Nf6 {Whenever White tries to go for f2-f3 we can just take Bc5 and we have an excellent pressure to the center and our rook development would be pretty obvious and successful. White doesn't have a pleasant play and the threat of Qd7!? to play g7-g5 is very annoying.} 9. O-O Na6 {A very common way of developing. Since Nhf5 and f3 and Qc2 are different threats, we remain flexible.} 10. Qc2 (10. d3 exd3 11. exd3 Be7 12. Nhf5 O-O 13. d4 Nc7 $15 {Black was doing great in the only game we have between GMs. 1-0 (40) Andriasian,Z (2611)-Riazantsev,A (2692) Dubai 2014}) 10... Qd7 $5 {One of the ways to have an interesting game. We are threatening Nb4+g5, so White is forced to take on e4.} 11. Bxe4 Nb4 12. Qb1 Nxa2 $132 {We will likely take on c1 and develop the f8 bishop and short castle. White has a bit more of a center, but with both bishops, a very safe pawn structure, and a majority on the queenside, I'd be quite happy with the imbalance.}) 7... Qe7 $1 $146 {After checking this line for a While I realized this novelty adds some spice to the position and can put White into serious trouble. For now b5 or f6 are immediate threats. In comparison to the crazy 7. ... Be6 8. Qc2! f6 9. Ng4! it is much safer and more logical for Black. You will need to remember it well, but I feel it is far less complicated and unbalanced.} 8. f4 (8. d4 Be6 {8. ... f6? Ne3 and White is much better. With this move order we force the c4 knight to the weird d2 square.} 9. Nd2 {A must, considering f6 and Qb4+ are very strong replies to any other move.} f6 10. Nec4 {10. Nxe4 Bd5! and we are close to winning already.} f5 {[%csl Rc4,Rd2] We are a bit behind on development, but usually White has better knights.} 11. O-O (11. b3 Nf6 12. Ba3 Qc7 {And we will end up castling long, as we have a powerful center.}) 11... Nf6 12. f3 (12. b3 b5 $1 {[%csl Rd2]} 13. Ba3 (13. Ne3 Nd5 $1 {We prevent f3 and We can finally move the queen away and finish developing.}) (13. Ne5 Nbd7 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Gd7e5,Gf6d5] We want to take and play Nd5 and Whites d2 knight just cries.}) 13... Qd7 {[%cal Ge8f7,Gf7g8]} 14. Bxf8 Rxf8 15. Na5 {[%cal Gb3b4,Ga2a3]} Na6 $1 $15 {[%csl Ra5,Rd2][%cal Gc6c5] Important move to prevent a3-b4.}) 12... exf3 13. exf3 Na6 $11 {[%cal Ge8c8] After castle and Nc7 we are in control.}) 8... Be6 {[%cal Gf7f6] Again f6 is an inmediate threat.} 9. Ne3 Nd7 10. Bxe4 Nxe5 11. fxe5 O-O-O {[%csl Re5]} 12. b3 Qg5 13. d4 Bb4+ 14. Kf2 Qe7 $132 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gc8b8] Now f6 is coming. White has some serious issues.} 15. Nf5 (15. Qd3 $1 {[%cal Ge4c6] Bxc6 is such an insane threat but we could even ignore it with f6.} Kb8 {[%cal Gf7f6] This is much more healthy and f6 is coming to get you.}) 15... Bxf5 16. Bxf5+ Kb8 17. Be3 Bc5 $132 {Now we go for Bb6 and f6 and White is so exposed in exchange for just a pawn.}) 4... e6 5. c4 dxc4 {As I said earlier, we want to prevent cxd5 ideas. Riazantsev was quite adept at this line many years ago.} 6. a4 {The most played line.} (6. b3 cxb3 7. Qxb3 (7. axb3 $15 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gg8f6,Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Gh7h6] With the queens this is terrible for White, as our queenside is safe.}) (7. Na3 {[%cal Gd1b3] White might try to play Qb3 without worrying about Qb6 forcing the queen exchange. White doesn't really care about the a2 pawn as we are so far behind on development and our queenside is exposed as the light-squared bishop is out of the pawnchain.} Nf6 8. Qxb3 Qb6 9. Qc4 Qa5 10. Nc2 Be4 $1 $15 {[%cal Gc6c5] What I like about this variation is how White has many appealing moves and can suddenly get into a worse position. After c5 we control the center and get an excellent square for the bishop on c6, countering the Whites plan.}) 7... Qb6 8. d3 {[%cal Gb3c2] White would love to avoid the queen exchange and then play Nbd2-Nc4 and press through the c and b files.} Qxb3 $1 $146 {With a bit of precision, Black should be fine.} 9. axb3 Nf6 10. Nbd2 Nbd7 11. Nc4 Bg4 {With this move we always threaten e2 and prevent Nd4 winning a tempo.} (11... Bb4 $6 12. Ba3 Bxa3 13. Rxa3 Ke7 14. Na5 Rab8 15. Nd4 $16 {0-1 (74) Fressinet,L (2702)-Vitiugov,N (2725) Berlin 2015}) 12. Na5 Rb8 13. Bf4 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 e5 $11 {We are doing fine. White still has some pressure but I see no dynamic trend to increase it, and White will need to have patience or we will be able to make our extra pawn count.}) (6. Na3 {A typical move. Played by many +2700, but wrong.} Bxa3 7. bxa3 Be4 {As you have seen quite often if we can get our light-squared bishop into the game, we are more than happy.} 8. Bb2 Nf6 9. Qc1 b5 $15 {0-1 (51) Zhang,Z (2619) -Vitiugov,N (2725) Berlin 2015}) (6. Ne5 Qd4 $11) (6. Nh4 {This weird move has been played by Svane recently. He basically plays only Nf3-g3-Bg2 in titled Tuesday, so it's a good source of interesting ideas. For now, compared to b2-b3, White wants to kill the f5 bishop so b3-Qxb3 is not countered with Qb6, forcing the queen exchange.} Bg4 {[%csl Ge2] White wants to play b3-Qxb3, with this move it is not so easy.} 7. Nc3 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gb2b3] Without the previous input, it is really hard to understand why Nc3 makes sense here.} (7. Na3 Bxa3 8. bxa3 Ne7 $132 {[%csl Gf5,Gg6][%cal Gb8d7,Gd8c7] We accommodate the comeback of our bishop to the b1-h7 diagonal and we have an excellent and peaceful development. White would still need to defend e2 and then try to take the c4 pawn in good fashion, but we can afford to play a6-b5 now.}) 7... Bb4 {We insist on the same idea.} 8. Qc2 Be7 $1 {With the queen on c2 we have more pressure on e2 and we can gain a tempo later on with Bf5 or with Nf5-Nd4.} 9. b3 $1 {Finally. 9. Nf3 is too slow and suddenly, Nd7 or really any move is safe. We need to be aware of the a3-f8 diagonal. That's why White can afford to play with this style. Also remember how our light-squared bishop is in the "air" still.} Nh6 $1 {We want to threaten Bxh4 but we also want to castle. We cannot start with Bxh4 as Ba3! would be a resource later on. Now we could take on h4 and play 0-0 or just go for Nf5-Bxf3-Nd4 in case of Nf3 retreat. You see how well White needs to understand these lines to play it according to the engine.}) 6... Nf6 7. Na3 Bxa3 8. Rxa3 O-O 9. b3 c3 $1 $146 {We always need to have an answer to opening the queenside and exposing ourselves to d2-d3 closing the f5 bishop for a while.} 10. d3 (10. dxc3 Be4 $132 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gc6c5] Now after Qe7-c5 we have the easiest gameplay, and White needs to be very creative. Considering this move order is very specific and good for White, I'd say I'm pretty satisfied to leave it where our next few moves are pretty simple and logical.}) 10... Bg4 $132 {[%cal Gf6d5,Gg4f3] Now Nd5 or Bxf3-Nd5-Qf6!? is very tricky for White.} *

