1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c6 3. c4 Nf6 4. Bg2 (4. Qc2 $5 {White can try to defend c4 and prevent Bf5.} Bg4 {As much as I can I want to keep up with the main ideal setup, taking out the bishop.} 5. Bg2 e6 6. O-O Be7 7. d3 O-O {[%cal Gh7h6,Gg4f5] Our dream now would be to reroute the bishop to h7.} 8. h3 Bh5 9. g4 Bg6 10. Ne5 Nbd7 11. Nxg6 hxg6 $11 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Ge7d6,Gd8e7] After Bd6-Qe7 we might even have Nh7-f5 plans to cheer for the win besides the obvious e6-e5.}) 4... Bg4 $5 {At first I wanted to propose 4. ... dxc4, as I played it many times, but this felt very safe and interesting in practice. Since this course aims to achieve a solid and reliable setup, it makes more sense to give practical approaches.} 5. Ne5 (5. cxd5 Bxf3 $11 {[%cal Gc6d5] This is just very safe. You have tons of games.} 6. Bxf3 cxd5 7. O-O (7. Qb3 Qd7 $11 {[%cal Gb8c6,Ge7e6] And now White might be experiencing the ghost limb syndrome without Ne5 being available.}) (7. d4 e6 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. e3 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Bd2 Rc8 12. Rc1 {[%cal Gd8d7,Gg7g6,Gh7h5,Yf8d8,Yc6e7,Ye7f5] Here I'd prefer to go for something like Qd7-g6-h5-Kg7 to consolidate our light squares and create some breaking points (g6-g5, h5-h4, Ng4) that can help us in the long run and then see if doubling the rooks is good or if some e6-e5 might be tempting. We can afford to play like this since White did commit to d4 and to e3. 0-1 (38) Wen,Y (2573) -Wang,H (2713) China 2015}) 7... Nc6 8. d3 e6 $132 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Yf8c8] Developing the bishop through e7 and then castle followed by taking out the queen and looking for the c file should work efficiently most of the time. White did not commit to d3-d4, so it has a bit more flexibility and we should be more consistent with moves like Rfc8 to get ahead of any e2-e4 or Be3-Nf3-Nd4 getting more pressure into our queenside while our f6 knight is a bit passive.}) (5. O-O e6 6. d4 {With this we transpose to 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 variation.} (6. h3 Bxf3 {Now we can just take.} 7. Bxf3 dxc4 8. Qc2 Nbd7 $1 $132 {[%cal Gd7b6,Yd7e5] Since White cannot take comfortably, we are more than fine and we solved the issue with the light squared bishop.}) 6... Nbd7 7. h3 Bf5 $11 {[%cal Gh7h6] Now it's too late for White to try h3 and we have this special move back as Nh4 is not a threat.} 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Qb3 Qb6 10. Qe3+ Be7 11. Nc3 {1-0 (54) Gukesh,D (2684)-Keymer, V (2686) Biel 2022} (11. Nh4 Bc2 $5 $132 {[%cal Gh7h6,Yd7f8,Yf8e6,Yb6d8] We just want to play Qd8 and castle. With Bc2 we distract White pieces enough to gain a couple of key tempis as h6-Bh7 would be great if possible, so 12. Nc3 is not possible.} 12. Na3 Bg6 13. Nxg6 hxg6 14. Nb1 Nf8 $1 $132 {[%cal Gf8e6,Ye8g8,Yg6g5]}) 11... Ne4 $1 $11 {Would immediately get an edge for Black.}) (5. h3 Bxf3 $1 {It is very important to avoid Bh5 i'd say. I think it might transpose to some critical variations that are not worth memorizing.} 6. Bxf3 e5 $5 {[%cal Gb8c6] This feels too simple for Black. Three wins in classical time control show it. We have a very pleasant development.} 7. Qb3 Qb6 8. Qc2 d4 $5 {[%csl Rb4,Rc5][%cal Ga7a5,Gb8d7,Gb8a6] We got all the dark squares so White doesn't have the best Benoni at all.}) (5. Qb3 Qb6 {To understand these structures, you can have a rule of thumb. If White played Qxb6 axb6, we would love to retake on d5 with the f6 knight. Otherwise we are left with a very uncomfortable long-term weakness with the isolated doubled pawns.} 6. d3 (6. Qxb6 axb6 7. cxd5 Nxd5 $1 $15 {[%cal Ya8a2,Gb8d7,Ge7e6,Yf7f6] White has a very weak queenside.}) (6. cxd5 Qxb3 $1 {For instance here 6. ... cxd5 wouldn't be that bad, but yeah, this is better.} 7. axb3 Bxf3 $1 {The worst case scenario would be to have cxd5 and then allow White to trap our light-squared bishop outside the pawnchain. After an eventual d2-d3, White has all the time in the world to pressure the queenside and prepare e2-e4 whenever needed. Here 7. ... cxd5 wouldn't be bad specifically as 8. Ne5 Bd7! and we find meaning to the bishop. That's why these lines have always been considered tricky for Black.} 8. Bxf3 cxd5 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gb8c6,Ge8d7,Yf8c5,Yh8c8] Better pawn structure, no weaknesses, all to the queenside. Easy.}) (6. Ne5 e6 $1 {We don't mind giving up the bishop pair now. It wouldn't be logical to change the approach , which is the best move. Here, you need to know how to react to some changes.} 7. cxd5 (7. Qxb6 axb6 8. cxd5 exd5 $1 {As we said, we don't want the isolated doubled pawns. Black has a pleasant edge as the doubled pawns now help increase the pressure on the queenside and activate our rook for free.}) (7. Nxg4 Nxg4 8. O-O Bc5 9. e3 d4 $5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gg4e5,Gb8a6] Would be a nice receipt as we get a flavour of a Trompowsky and full control of light and dark squares.}) 7... exd5 $1 {7. ... cxd5????????? would be very sad after 8. Qa4+! (Not 8. Nxg4 as Qc6 is saving us later).} (7... Qxb3 8. axb3 {[%cal Gd2d3,Gc1e3,Yg2b7,Ye3a7] White can exploit this pawnchain better,  as d3-Be3 is a serious plan and we have missing components on the queenside.} cxd5 9. Nc3 Nc6 $1 {This is fine for Black according to engine. But as I said before, it is very tricky in practice and the pawnchain is incredibly volatile. If you remember precisely and have it well prepared, go ahead. But this kind of endgame usually have some issues with the LightSquared bishop trapped outside the pawn chain.}) 8. Nxg4 Nxg4 {[%cal Gb6b3,Yb8a6,Ya6b4]} 9. Qf3 Nf6 $132 {[%cal Gf8d6,Ge8g8,Gf8e8,Ga7a5,Gb8d7] We have a pawn chain that counters very well the g2 bishop and our game plan is very straightforward, put pieces into the center!.}) 6... Nbd7 7. Be3 {This is a well-known plan. White forces the queen exchange and then dreams of playing cxd5, cxd5 Nd4!-f4-h3-g4-Nd2-Bf2-e4 and we would only be able to watch as our position collapses. But here we have an immediate reaction into the center.} Qxb3 8. axb3 e5 $132 {[%cal Gf8d6,Yg4f3,Yd7c5]}) 5... Bf5 $5 {5. ... Be6 is more or less refuted but this move fits well with our goals and works.} 6. cxd5 (6. Qb3 Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7e5]} 7. Nxd7 (7. d4 {This is the most precise continuation.} Qb6 {Now it is more pleasant to counter Qb3 like this.} 8. Nxd7 (8. cxd5 {Any move is more or less fine so it shouldn't worry too much.} Qxb3 9. axb3 cxd5 10. Nc3 e6 $11 {[%cal Gf8b4,Ge8e7,Ge8g8]}) 8... Kxd7 $1 {The king is temporarily bad, but we are very safe, and the possible queen exchange makes it logical.} 9. Nc3 e6 10. c5 Qxb3 11. axb3 Be7 {[%cal Gh7h6,Gg7g5]}) 7... Qxd7 $11 {This is just safe.} 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Nc3 Rd8 $1 $132 {[%cal Gd5d4,Ge7e5] I feel this is a bit more precise than the usual e6 and getting our bishop on f5 a bit out of the game for a while. Having exchanged the queenside knight we might face practical problems.}) 6... cxd5 7. O-O $5 {Ding played this, so we must be aware.} (7. Qb3 {Now it works  poorly as we have an extra move.} Nc6 $1 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. d3 e5 $1 $146 10. O-O Be7 $15 {And we have the center for free. White feels the weight of playing a useless Qb3.}) (7. Qa4+ Bd7 8. Nxd7 Qxd7 $132 {[%cal Ge8d7,Gb8c6,Ge7e6] We have a very well known endgame.}) (7. Nc3 Nc6 8. Nxc6 (8. Qa4 Bd7 $132 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gf8e7,Ge8g8]}) 8... bxc6 $132 {[%cal Ge7e5,Gf8e7] Again we aim on going for e5 and having a healthy center so our c6 pawn is not a problem per se.}) 7... Nbd7 (7... Nc6 $5 {This is unknown territory.} 8. Nxc6 bxc6 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 9. d3 {Now with an extra tempo this is far more challenging.} e5 $5 10. e4 $1 {Otherwise we are pretty happy to play Be6-Be7.} Bg4 (10... dxe4 11. Qc2 $1 $16 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gd3e4] And we would be strategically busted.}) 11. Qe1 {The best move.} (11. Qc2 Rc8 12. Bg5 Be7 $132 {Our pawnchain is not ideal but the gameplan is very straightforward  all to the center.}) 11... Bd6 $132 {[%cal Ga8b8] It is likely that we need to give up a pawn to castle quickly. But after Rb8 I'd be pretty satisfied with the compensation.}) 8. d4 e6 9. Nc3 {[%cal Gg3g4] And now ideas with g3-g4 might get seriously annoying.} Be7 10. g4 $5 $146 {It is quite unlikely you would ever face this, but hey engines go fast.} (10. Qb3 O-O $5 $132 {[%cal Gd7e5,Gf6d7] Black is superfine.} 11. Qxb7 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. Be3 Nxe5 14. Rad1 {1-0 (22) Poley,V (2306) -Ingbrandt,J (2369) Sweden 2014} Bf6 $1 $36 {[%cal Gd8c8,Gd8a5,Ge5c4]}) 10... Nxe5 11. gxf5 Nc6 $132 {White needs to keep playing flawlessly dynamic and we are pretty safe.} *

