1. Nf3 {In this Chapter, we have some weird ideas that force us to be more flexible.} d5 2. b3 {Our setup works especially well against passive approaches.} (2. d3 $5 {Rapport and Grischuk played tons of times this move order and we might need to switch a bit as playing 2. ... c6 3. e4! and we get into a Carokhan for no reason.} Nc6 {[%cal Ge7e5] Might be the easiest play method. Looking for e5. In the case of 3. d4 Bf5, we can develop normally with h6-e6-Nf6.} (2... Bf5 3. c4 $1 {There is no real theory of this approach, but if you aim to play Bf5 no matter what, your opponent might get smart in the move order.} dxc4 4. e4 Bg4 5. d4 $14 {Funnily after Nc6 we get into a Chigorin :).}) 3. d4 (3. g3 {Suddenly, we get into a Pirc. I'll try to give some simple guidelines.} e5 4. Bg2 Be6 {This is the easiest setup, I'd say. We just take e4 or c4 and go for Qd7-0-0-0.} 5. O-O Qd7 $1 6. Ng5 (6. Nc3 f6 7. e4 d4 8. Ne2 O-O-O $17 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gh7h5] This is terrible for White.}) (6. e4 dxe4 7. dxe4 O-O-O 8. Qe2 Bc5 {[%cal Gf7f6,Gg8e7,Yc6d4] Many moves are good but this one feels the easiest.}) 6... Bg4 $15 {White is already much worse.}) (3. Nbd2 e5 4. e4 Nf6 5. Be2 Bd6 {As a Phillidor player, I feel this is the safest approach if you don't have experience against it.} 6. O-O O-O 7. c3 a5 8. Re1 Re8 {[%cal Gh7h6]} 9. a4 h6 {[%cal Gc8e6]} 10. exd5 Nxd5 $132 {[%cal Gc8f5,Yd8f6,Ya8d8] Our development is very easy and having the bishop on d6 prevents any shenanigans.}) 3... Bf5 4. g3 e6 {[%cal Gh7h6,Gg8f6]}) 2... c6 3. d3 (3. Bb2 h6 $1 {No need to get exposed to Nh4 ideas.} 4. e3 Bf5 5. c4 $5 {This setup for White doesn't do any harm. We can just develop quite freely and White eventually would need to say something into the center, as we aim to play Nf6-e6-Nbd7-Bd6-e5.} e6 6. d4 (6. Be2 Nf6 7. Nc3 Nbd7 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gd8e7] Black is already much better after Bd6-Qe7. We a great London.}) 6... Nf6 7. Bd3 Bb4+ 8. Bc3 Bd6 $15 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gd8e7,Gb8d7] 0-1 (38) Jurcik,M (2358) -Basso,P (2563) Ulcinj 2019}) 3... Bf5 {Now it is a bit different. We can play e5 in one go later on.} (3... h6 $6 4. e4 $1 $14) 4. Nh4 Bg4 5. h3 Bh5 6. g3 e5 $15 {[%cal Gf7f6] Since we skipped Nf6, we can even play f6, and the Whites plan doesn't make that much sense anymore.} *

