1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 {This is one of the most popular setups lately. Playing like an Orthodox setup with Black always has some annoyances if White plays later with b3-Bb2 and even some g3-Bg2 after taking on d5 vs b6. I really hated those structures, as they dragged the game for so long and we barely have counterplay. That's why I tried to look for a more consistent setup and developed this course.} c6 3. c4 Nf6 {Since Qb3 is in the air, we must first play this move.} 4. Nc3 (4. b3 {Now it is a bit different.} Bf5 5. Bb2 e6 (5... h6 6. Bxf6 $5 $14 {This might be very annoying in practice. No one really played it but it looks like a pleasant weapon for White, breaking our pawn structure.} gxf6 {[%cal Gh6h5]}) 6. Nh4 {This is the only move order that can prevent our plan, but it is nothing special.} Be4 $1 $146 {[%cal Gf8b4] Since Bb4+ is coming. We are not worried about d2-d3.} 7. Nc3 h6 8. Nxe4 dxe4 {[%csl Rh4]} 9. g3 Nbd7 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gf8d6,Gd8e7] White is in danger.} 10. f3 Be7 {[%cal Gf6h7]} 11. fxe4 Nxe4 12. Qc2 Bf6 $11 {We have a more solid and sound position.}) 4... a6 $5 {I'd say this is the easiest and most logical way to play if we want to follow up with Bf5 ever. Now 5. b3 is one of the most played moves but we get an excellent position and 5. d4 transposes to a safe Chebanenko.} 5. Qc2 {[%csl Gf5] Preventing Bf5.} (5. b3 Bf5 6. Nh4 {This might be the best version for White to play Nh4. But again, pay attention to how e5 is not controlled.} Bg6 7. Nxg6 hxg6 8. d4 (8. Bb2 e5 $11) 8... e6 {[%cal Gf8b4,Gb4c3,Yf6e4] We have an excellent version of the Slav as b3 is absurd. Since you already play the Slav, this should be a piece of cake for you.}) (5. Be2 {We shift into a comfortable variation of the Queen's gambit. Against 5. h3, we can play the same way.} dxc4 6. Bxc4 e6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc6c5] We want to shift to a known queens gambit that is very practical.} 7. d4 b5 8. Bb3 {This is known to be a bit tricky.} (8. Bd3 c5 {[%cal Gb8d7] We prioritize Nbd7 and the rest is easy to find.}) 8... c5 9. O-O (9. e4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 {[%cal Gb3e6] Some Bxe6 ideas happen, so we need to be careful.} Nbd7 {[%cal Gf8c5,Gc8b7]} 11. Be3 Bb7 (11... Bc5 12. Bxe6 $1 $16) 12. O-O Bb4 $132 {[%cal Ge8g8]}) 9... Bb7 10. e4 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nbd7 12. Re1 Ne5 $5 $11 {[%csl Rb3,Rc3][%cal Gf8c5] Some sacrifices like Nd5 or Bd5 can happen,  but we can just prioritize development with 13. ... Nfd7!? and 13. ... Qd7! and we are more than fine.}) 5... g6 $1 {We change a bit the style of the position but being able to play Bf5 later makes it similarly logical and practical.} 6. b3 Bg7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Be2 (8. d4 Bf5 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 b5 $11 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gb8d7] Black is very safe and sound. After Nbd7-Qb6b7-e6 we can try to take advantage of the dark-squared white bishop through the weaker light squares.}) 8... Bf5 $11 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ge7e5]} *

