1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 c6 3. c4 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 $5 5. d4 {This is not part of the course, but we will give some guidelines as you might not play this Chebanenko variation. White already played e2-e3, so we dodged the most critical variations.} (5. b3 Bf5 6. Nh4 {This might be the best version for White to play Nh4. But again, pay attention to how e5 is not controlled.} Bg6 7. Nxg6 hxg6 8. Bb2 (8. d4 e6 {[%cal Gf8b4,Gb4c3,Yf6e4] We have an excellent version of the Slav as b3 is absurd. Since you already play the Slav, this should be a piece of cake for you.}) 8... e5 $11) 5... e6 {5. Bf5 is extremely risky after Ne5-Qb3 variations, so it is quite unlikely we get any desired similar position. That's why I prefer to change the approach since we play Bf5 WHENEVER POSSIBLE, not to make us suffer.} 6. c5 {White tries to build a pyramid to take advantage of 4. ... a6.} (6. b3 Bb4 {As in the Catalan, we want to force an awkward Bd2 first.} 7. Bd2 Nbd7 8. Bd3 O-O {[%cal Gb4d6,Ge6e5]} 9. O-O Bd6 {[%csl Rd2] Now the bishop is terrible on d2.} 10. Qc2 {[%cal Ge3e4]} (10. e4 $11 dxc4 11. bxc4 e5 $1 {This pawn exchange pattern will help you understand these structures.} 12. c5 {Otherwise, White would lose all control on the dark squares.} Bc7 13. Na4 exd4 14. h3 Re8 {[%cal Gh7h6] We are safe and White cannot make easy progress as Nxd4 is always followed by Ne5!. We can go for h6 first and then Nf8-Ng6-Nh5. We have all the minor pieces pointing to the Kingside. An eventual Rb8 would secure our bishop pair and prevent any Nb6, so it is also recommended.}) (10. Re1 h6 $1 11. h3 e5 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. e4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Rxe4 (15. Bxe4 exd4 $11) 15... Nf6 $11 {The key difference. Including h6-h3 made Bg5 is impossible and has an amazing setup. We can even follow up with e5-e4 sacrifice to seize the light squares.}) 10... h6 {As usual we take advantage of e4 dxc4! and e5 idea.} 11. Rad1 e5 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Ne2 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Gc8e6]} Be6 {[%cal Ga8c8] After Rc8 we look for Bg4 to get rid of the light-squared bishop or Ng4 and we have a very dynamic isolated pawn.}) (6. Qc2 c5 {[%cal Yc8c2] Generally, in QGD, whenever the Queen is on c2, c5 gets more interesting. Here we just need to know a precise move order and that's all.} 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Be2 Nc6 9. O-O Be6 10. Rd1 Nb4 $1 11. Qb1 (11. Qd2 Ne4 $11) 11... Qc8 $132 {[%cal Ge6f5,Yc5c4] The threat of Bf5 followed by c4 makes it quite easy to play.}) (6. Bd3 dxc4 7. Bxc4 b5 {We transpose again to the QGA we explained in another chapter.}) 6... b6 7. cxb6 Qxb6 8. Bd3 (8. Na4 Qc7 $5 $132 {[%cal Ga6a5,Gc8a6,Gf8d6,Gb8d7]}) 8... a5 9. O-O (9. Na4 Qc7 $5 $132 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gc8a6,Gf8d6,Gh7h6,Gf6d7,Ge8g8,Gf8c8]}) 9... Ba6 $132 {After exchanging those bishops, White lacks pressure on the center and space to threaten c6 efficiently. We have even good chances to play c6-c5 in the future.} *

