1. c4 {Finally, we will look mostly at the Panov and how to approach it without remembering 1500 moves.} c6 2. e4 $5 {The Panov is also a weapon we must consider as c4 players like happy open positions, not dark solid slavs.} (2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. Qc2 {Preventing Bf5 but definetely allowing us to get advantage.} e5 5. d3 h6 $15 {[%cal Gf8d6,Ge8g8] Very safe and easy advantage.}) (2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 Bf5 $11 {White doesn't have any special ideas here.}) 2... d5 3. exd5 (3. cxd5 cxd5 4. e5 {White tries to enter French-like structures where the tension on d4 was solved, so the b1 knight can develop smoothly through c3. Here, you just need to know a move.} Qa5 $1 $15 {And White cannot continue with his idea.}) 3... cxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3 (6. Bg5 dxc4 {The easiest solution i'd say.} 7. Bxc4 (7. d5 Ne5 8. Qd4 h6 $1 {We force White bishop to take a path.} 9. Bf4 {Only sensible move. Against any c1-e3 move, Nd3+ would be excellent now. Bh4 was a bit too slow after Ng6 followed by e5!.}) 7... h6 {We force the bishop to take a path.} 8. Bh4 (8. Bf4 e6 9. Nf3 Bd6 {[%csl Rf4]} 10. Ne5 {Only serious move.} O-O $11 {[%cal Gd8b6]} 11. O-O Qb6 $11 {[%cal Gd6b8,Gf8d8] Followed by Bb8 or Rd8 and we would be able to pressure the isolated pawn.}) (8. Bxf6 exf6 $15 {[%cal Gf8d6] We have an insanely good blockade on d6.}) 8... e6 $11 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Yf6h5] After castling we just play Nh5 and we are more than fine.}) (6. Bf4 g6 $1 7. c5 Bg7 8. Bb5 O-O 9. Nge2 {Taking on c6 first would allow us Nd7-e5.} e5 $1 $15 {[%cal Gf6h5]}) 6... a6 $5 {This move is quite trendy lately beeing Carlsen a premium customer.} 7. Bg5 (7. c5 Bg4 8. Be2 e6 9. O-O g6 $132 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gf6d7] We achieve the key counterplay through the center. We can even go for e6-e5 directly without Nd7 if possible after castling.}) (7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Bc4 Be6 9. Bb3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Bxb3 11. axb3 e6 $11 {[%cal Gf8e7,Gd8d7,Gf8d8,Ga8c8] We will put everything into place with ease and then pressure the center. White has a poor -4 out of 16 games.}) (7. h3 $5 dxc4 {The easiest way. As going for g6 would justify h3, preventing Bg4.} 8. Bxc4 e6 {[%cal Gb7b5] Black is going great thanks to a quick b5-Nb4 or Ne5.}) 7... Be6 {Now 7. ... dxc4? would be too slow as a6 is not that useful.} 8. c5 {Might be the most accurate move order.} (8. Be2 g6 9. Bxf6 exf6 10. c5 {Otherwise, we have an excellent blockade.} (10. O-O Bg7 $11 11. c5 g5 $5 $132 12. b4 g4 13. Ne1 f5 14. Nc2 Qf6 15. b5 Nxd4 16. bxa6 bxa6 17. Nxd4 Qxd4 18. Qxd4 Bxd4 19. Rac1 Bxc3 20. Rxc3 Kd7 21. f3 Rhb8 22. Bd3 h5 23. c6+ Kd6 24. c7 Rc8 25. Rfc1 Bd7 26. Kf2 f4 27. g3 fxg3+ 28. hxg3 gxf3 29. Kxf3 a5 30. Kf4 a4 31. a3 Ra5 32. Bf5 Ra7 33. Bxd7 Kxd7 34. Rc5 Raxc7 35. Rxd5+ Ke6 36. Rxc7 Rxc7 37. Rd4 Ra7 38. Kg5 Ra5+ 39. Kh4 Kf6 40. Rb4 Kg6 41. Rc4 f6 42. Rb4 Ra7 43. Rf4 Ra6 44. Rb4 Ra7 45. Rf4 Ra5 {½-½ (45) Graf,F (2493)-Erdos,V (2661) Germany 2013}) 10... g5 $1 11. O-O g4 12. Ne1 f5 13. Nc2 Qf6 $15 {[%cal Gf5f4,Gf8g7] Feels like a justified approach and White has problems with Bg7 or f4-f3.}) (8. Rc1 g6 9. Be2 Bg7 10. c5 Ne4 11. Bf4 O-O 12. O-O Bg4 13. Na4 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Bxd4 (14... Nxd4 $17) 15. Nb6 Ra7 16. b4 e5 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Bh6 Nxb4 19. Bxf8 Kxf8 20. Kh1 Kg7 21. f3 Nd3 22. Rc2 Bxc5 23. fxe4 Nf2+ 24. Rcxf2 Qxd1 25. Rxf7+ Kg8 26. Rf8+ Bxf8 27. Rxd1 Bc5 28. Rd8+ Kg7 29. Rd7+ Kh6 30. Nc8 Ra8 31. Rc7 b6 32. g3 a5 33. a4 Rb8 34. Kg2 Bb4 35. Na7 Rd8 36. h4 Rd2+ 37. Kh3 Rd3 38. Rc1 Bc5 39. Nc6 Re3 40. Rc4 Kg7 41. Nxe5 Bd6 {0-1 (41) Aronian,L (2745)-Carlsen,M (2853) Chess.com INT 2023}) 8... g6 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. h3 {[%csl Re6] White has created a practical problem on our light-squared bishop.} Nd7 $1 {[%csl Rd4] We can counter the White idea with a bit of precision.} (10... O-O 11. O-O $14 {½-½ (71) Paravyan,D (2617) -Grandelius,N (2672) Chess.com INT 2022}) 11. Bc2 (11. Ne2 f6 $1 {[%cal Ge6f7,Ge8g8,Ge7e5]}) 11... b6 $132 {[%cal Yd8b6]} *

