1. c4 c6 2. e4 $5 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. cxd5 Nf6 5. Bb5+ {This is not especially dangerous, but I lost against it so it is not stupid.} (5. Nc3 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Bb5 e6 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gc8d7,Ge8g8] Followed by Bd6-0-0-Bd7. White doesn't have a threatening square for the c1 bishop, and we finish the development swiftly. 7. ... g6 is very interesting but we are analyzing the panov through 1. c4, so it is not too likely so I prefer to give safe and practical ideas. You can dig deeper if you want.}) (5. Qa4+ {Here you just need to know the precise move order.} Nbd7 6. Nc3 g6 7. Bc4 Bg7 8. Nf3 (8. d3 a6) 8... a6 $1 {This kinda new line kills the variation.} 9. d3 Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 10. Qd1 (10. Bb3 b5 11. Qf4 (11. Qh4 {This forces us into a tricky variation (as we might be afraid to lose a pawn later on).} Nc5 12. O-O Nxb3 13. axb3 Nxd5 14. Bh6 O-O $1 15. Nxd5 Qxd5 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Qxe7 Bb7 $15 {[%csl Rb2,Rb3,Rd3]}) 11... Bb7 {[%cal Gd7c5]} 12. Be3 O-O 13. O-O {Here we have many interesting pawn sacrifices.} b4 $11 14. Qxb4 Bxd5 15. Qd4 Bxb3 16. axb3 Rxb3 17. Rfb1 Qb8 18. Rxa6 Rxb2 19. Rxb2 Qxb2 20. Ra2 Qb8 21. Ra3 Rc8 22. Bd2 Nc5 23. Bf4 Qb7 24. Be5 Qb2 {0-1 (24) Bhakti,K (2231)-Gagare,S (2446) Mumbai 2014}) 10... b5 11. Bb3 Bb7 12. Bf4 Rc8 13. d6 O-O $15 {[%csl Gb7,Gg7][%cal Gd7c5,Yf8d8] We have more than compensation. White pieces don't have any coordination.}) 5... Nbd7 6. Nf3 (6. Nc3 a6 7. Be2 (7. Qa4 g6 8. Nf3 Bg7 9. O-O O-O {[%cal Gd7b6]} 10. Bxd7 Nxd7 $15 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gd7b6]}) 7... Nb6 $11) 6... a6 $1 {[%cal Gb7b5] Taking on d5 It is a soft mistake, as we have a very weird knight on d7. After b5-Bb7 we achieve a nice blockade on d5 and White is in danger.} *

