{[#]} 5... h6 $1 {This is a significant move in order to punish the White setup. This way we prevent c4-cxd5 setups and we have a great practical answer that gave me a winning position against a strong GM.} 6. Nfd2 $5 {[%cal Ge2e4] This plan is pretty common against the London. White wants to push for e4 without wasting tempos with the queen or the rook. It is the most challenging for Black, as you can get steamrolled by the e,f, and g pawns in the blink of an eye.} Bh7 7. e4 Nf6 8. Nc3 Be7 9. f4 {White follows up with the usual expansion. Now, we don't want to castle too fast and justify g4-g5.} a5 {Doing some business on the queenside before castling looks smart. As we'll see plenty in this chapter, a5-a4 fits very well with the London-esque lines.} (9... O-O 10. g4 $5 $14 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gf4f5] The permanent threat of e4-e5 and/or f4-f5 is very unpleasant in practice.}) *

