{[#]} {How should Black continue?} 10... dxc4 11. bxc4 e5 $1 {This pawn exchange pattern will help you understand these structures.} 12. c5 {Otherwise, White would lose all control on the dark squares.} Bc7 13. Na4 exd4 14. h3 Re8 {[%cal Gh7h6] We are safe and White cannot make easy progress as Nxd4 is always followed by Ne5!. We can go for h6 first and then Nf8-Ng6-Nh5. We have all the minor pieces pointing to the Kingside. An eventual Rb8 would secure our bishop pair and prevent any Nb6, so it is also recommended.} *

